  "body": "I'm using two coredns instances. One uses the file plugin and the other uses the secondary plugin. After each change of a zone file, the transfer succeeds. The answers from the primary instance are correct. But the secondary starts to answer with the old and the new NS records (all other answers seem to be correct too):\r\n\r\nThis is the result after 4 changes to the zone file:\r\n```# dig -t NS example.org @localhost\r\n\r\n; <<>> DiG 9.9.5-9+deb8u14-Debian <<>> -t NS example.org @localhost\r\n;; global options: +cmd\r\n;; Got answer:\r\n;; ->>HEADER<<- opcode: QUERY, status: NOERROR, id: 60058\r\n;; flags: qr aa rd ra; QUERY: 1, ANSWER: 8, AUTHORITY: 0, ADDITIONAL: 1\r\n\r\n;; OPT PSEUDOSECTION:\r\n; EDNS: version: 0, flags:; udp: 4096\r\n;; QUESTION SECTION:\r\n;example.org.\t\tIN\tNS\r\n\r\n;; ANSWER SECTION:\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns1.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns2.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns1.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns2.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns1.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns2.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns1.example.net.\r\nexample.org.\t3600\tIN\tNS\tns2.example.net.\r\n\r\n;; Query time: 0 msec\r\n;; SERVER: ::1#53(::1)\r\n;; WHEN: Thu Jan 18 10:02:00 CET 2018\r\n;; MSG SIZE  rcvd: 178```",
